{"type":"message","id":"beb18e2c","parentId":"01a77737","timestamp":"2026-03-09T18:18:08.549Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking about where pink elephants (albino/pink-skinned elephants) are found on Earth. This is a general knowledge question, not a memory recall question. Let me answer from what I know.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"text","text":"Pink elephants — as in real ones — are albino or leucistic elephants with pinkish skin. Here's where they show up:\n\n### Asia\n- **Myanmar (Burma)** — The most famous source. White/pink elephants have been revered there for centuries. They're considered sacred and historically belonged to the king. Finding one was a major political event.\n- **Thailand** — Also deeply culturally significant. The Thai royal family has kept white elephants for centuries. The phrase \"white elephant\" (as in an unwanted gift) actually comes from the legend that Thai kings would gift rare albino elephants to courtiers they wanted to ruin — since you couldn't refuse a royal gift or put a sacred animal to work, but it was incredibly expensive to maintain.\n- **Sri Lanka, India** — Occasional sightings, but much rarer.\n\n### Africa\n- **South Africa** — A few documented cases, mostly in Kruger National Park and surrounding reserves. There's been a notable pink-skinned elephant calf spotted there.\n- **Botswana & Zimbabwe** — Rare sightings near the Okavango Delta and Hwange.\n\n### Why they're pink\nThey're not *bright* pink — it's more of a pinkish-grey. The skin lacks normal pigmentation, so blood vessels show through more visibly. They often look pinker when wet. Sun exposure is a real problem for them since they lack the protective dark pigment.\n\n### How rare?\nExtremely. There's no solid population count, but they're a tiny fraction of wild elephants. In Africa it's a genetic anomaly that pops up occasionally. In Southeast Asia, \"white elephants\" are slightly more documented because of the cultural tradition of seeking them out and keeping them in royal care.\n\nSo the short answer: **mostly Myanmar and Thailand** for the culturally famous ones, with **rare wild sightings in southern/eastern Africa**."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-opus-4-6","usage":{"input":3,"output":488,"cacheRead":14162,"cacheWrite":528,"totalTokens":15181,"cost":{"input":0.000015000000000000002,"output":0.0122,"cacheRead":0.007081,"cacheWrite":0.0033,"total":0.022596}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773080273268}}
